{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938010301/0485.xml":{"full_text":"COLLADAY SEES\nPROSPERITY RISE\nFORB. C. IN 1938\nTrade Board President\nAnalyzes Factors\nBy EDWARD F. COLLADAY\nPresident Washington Board of\nTrade\nAs the year comes to a close,\ntn appraisal of business conditions\nand trade activity in the District\nof Columbia makes a forecast for\n1938 an uncertain affair.\nDuring 1937, greater activity in\npractically all commonly accepted\n\u2022'barometer\u201d fields than in the\nImmediately preceding years was\napparent. The number of tele\nphones in use is now greater than\never before and the average num\nher of originating calls per day has\nIncreased substantially. In every\nEDWARD F. COLLADAY\nmonth during 1937 electric output\nwas greater than in the corre\nspending month ot 1936 Postal\nreceipts were at an all-time high\nand check transactions for the\nyear as a whole showed a markeo\nincrease. Up to September, the\ndepartment store index was about\n6 per cent above .ast year. Os great\nimportance to Washington is the\nfact that 1937 was probably the\ngreatest tourist year in history\nMore than three million people\nvisited our city in the first 11\nmonths of this year.\nEMPLOYMENT RISES\nEmployment conditions In\nWashington seem to be improved\nas indicated by the report of the\nPublic Employment Service which\nshowed that on December 1 there\nwere 19.1 per cent fewer per\nsons registered than on the same\nday a year before. During the\nfirst 11 months of 1937 there\nhave also been 17.3 per cent fewer\nnew applicants than there were\nin the corresponding period of\n1936 and placements in private\nIndustry were swelled.\nViewing the year as a whole\nit is readily apparent, therefore,\nthat business and commercial ac\ntivity in the District of Columbia\nwas still on the upgrade from\nthe 1933 low.\nThe fact that Washington\u2019s\npopulation has continued to grow\nand passed the 625,000 mark in\nJuly, according to Census Bureau\nestimates, gives further weight to\nthe belief that business in the fu\nture will continue to improve.\nDECLINE IN FALL\nThe disturbing item in the pic\nture is that beginning in Septem\nber there was a marked drop in\nbusiness activity. During the fall\nand early winter department-store\nsales fell behind the same months\nin 1936. Check transactions\nthrough the Washington Clearing\nHouse reflected this recession. At\nthe same time there has been a\nslight reduction in the number of\nFederal employes and, conse\nquently, in the Federal pay roll.\nWe believe that Washington\nhaviM stable employment condi\ntions, growing rapidly md becom\ning more important in the na\ntional economy as the years go by,\ncan expect a continuation of in\ncreased prosperity.\nFROM FIRE Or The MID\nNIGHT PROWLER!...\n-TOUIL i Insurance Policies Stock Certificates\nt IrtW/finifa/L Deeds Bonds\nW'' Mortgage Papers Jewelry\nflw*.\nSAFE\n4 -ft Put them m a safe Place such as a\nQ Private box in the Safe Deposit Vaults\n'VAULTS at the Munsey Trust Co.\n$3 A Year and Up\nTHE MUNSEY TRUST CO.\nPenna. Ave. Bet. 13th and 14th Sts. N. W.\nMUNSEY BUILDING\nMember- Federal Deposit Insurance Corf.\nTafapAona KE publie 1234\nBusiness Outlook Best\nSince \u201932\u2014-McGraw\nPublisher Sees Great Opportunities\nFor Industry to Expand\n\u201cThe year 1938 should not be a year of -depression. The\npresent period of recession, permitting certain necessary cor\nrections in commodity prices and inventories which grew too\nUTILE CHANGE\nIN 11. S. PAY ROLL\nNow that 1937 has passed into\nhistory, the interest of everyone\nis naturally centered on the busi\nness prospects for Washington\nduring the new year.\nWhile it is impossible to pre\ndict the future with certainty,\nthere are, nevertheless, many fac\ntors which should serve as a ba\nrometer of the business \u201cweather\u201d\nfor the coming months.\nCITY INSULATED\nIt is well to remember in con\nthe business prospects oi\nthe Capital that it is a city where\nthe commercial life is insulated\nfrom the rest of the country be\ncause of the stabilizing influence\nof Government employment.\nAlthough 1937 witnessed a\nslight drop from 1936 in the aver\nage of Government employment,\nhere, it must be remembered that\npart of the 1937 drop reflects a re\nclassification of Federal employes\ninaugurated- during June 1937,\nwhich eliminated from the month\nly employment reports those who\nwere on a part-time basis.\nWithout this change in the\nmethod of keeping the records the\ndifference between the 1936 and\n1937 employment averages would\nhave been negligible.\nA canvass of expert opinion in\ndicates theie will be very little\nchange in the total number of\npeople employed by the Federal\nGovernment in Washington dur\ning 1938, barring unforeseen de\nvelopments.\nPOPULATION GROWS\nWashington is continuing its\nrapid growth in population, ac\ncording to the latest estimate of\nthe United States Census Bureau\nThis reliable source of informa\ntion reveals that there are now\n627,000 residents of this city\u2014a\ngain of 8,000 in the short span\nof one year and a gain of 28 per\ncent since the 1930 census.\nThe present situation among\nWashington\u2019s retail stores, accord\ning to a well-informed merchant.\nis similar to that in 1933 when\nthere was a general stocking-up\nin anticipation of higher prices.\nOrdinarily this condition would\nhave brought about a large\namount of price-slashing in De\ncember, but a study of the news\npaper advertising in this period\nshowed a surprising lack of this\ntype of promotion. People close\nto the retail situation ascribe this\nrather unusual condition to the\nactive last-minute Christmas shop\nPing.\nSTORE SALES STABLE\nIf this is the case, retail stores\nwill find little need to feature\nclearance sales on as large a scale\nas might otherwise be necessary\nto keep their inventories low.\nSales by D. C. department stores\nfor 1937 were about the same as in\n1936, judging from the report of\nthe Federal Reserve Bank of Rich\nmond. And, based on this fact, the\ntotal retail sales in the capital dur\ning 1937 were approximately $377,\n000,000. This is a gain of 55 per\ncent over the 1933 figure.\nLeading retail executives say\nthat profits for the year 1937 com\npare favorably with 1936 in spite\ni of rising costs of operation due\nparticularly to increased taxes and\nhigher labor costs.\nBank clearances for 1937\ni reached a new high since 1933 in\nthe District of Columbia. And even\nthough automobile sales were off\n-about 10 per cent, it is significant\nto note that sales of cars in the\nhigher brackets showed an in\ncrease.\nrapidly in 1937, may last through\nthe first quarter, but no longer.\u201d\nThis is the conclusion of James\nH. McGraw, Jr., president of Mc-\nGraw-Hill Publishing Company, in\ndiscussion of the business outlook\nMcGraw is convinced there are\ngreat opportunities for industry I\nto eliminate waste, exploit new\ndevelopments, develop new mar\nkets, and catch up on long-de\nlayed improvements in plants and\nproducts.\nOUTLOOK BEST SINCE 32\nObstacles to these improve\nments created by laws,\u201d he says,\n\"may very likely be removed or\nminimized by a Congress which\nseems to understand better the\nneeas and problems of industry.\nPhe outlook for sound and sub\nstantial improvement as distin-\nguished from 'emergency measures\u2019\nseems to be oetter than at any\ntime since 1932.\n\u201cI strongly feel that the cur\nrent setback is intermediate. The\ngreat buying wave of last winter\nhas been succeeded by a strong\nretrenchment wave. This began\nin a spotty fashion about May of\n1937 and in the retail field gen\nerally there is a good prospect\nthat it will have been pretty fully\ncompleted by the end of January.\nBy that time inventories should\nbe exhausted\u2014or nearly so.\nRENEWED BUYING SEEN\n\u201cThis means that all kinds of\nbusinesses-manufacturers, whole\nsaler and retailers\u2014will be forced\nto resume forward buying. Even\nhand-to-mouth buying for current\nrequirements will turn the trend\nof business upward. A majority\nof industries already are shipping\nmore than they are producing.\ni \u2018Most industrialists who en\ndeavor to be foresighted will prob\nably be releasing plans for capital\nadditions and betterments by\nspring, whereas Industrialists who\nare more timid will be inclined\nto wait until Autumn, and will\nundoubtedly have to pay higher\nfor the privilege of such waiting.\u201d\nTan Washington Loan\nand Tboit Company\nMala OIHm: F Straet At Sth Waat End OHieai 17th Stiaat At O\nI\nPresents a Statement cf Condition of Its Banking Department\nON DECEMBER 31, 1937\nDeposits of 45,000 Customers $23,338,937.71\nTo Secure These Deposits the Bank has\n1. Cash in Vaults and Reserve in Fed-\neral Reserve and Other Banks $6,512,762.23\n2. U. S. Government Securities and\nOther Obligations, Government-\nguaranteed 7,896,088.03\n3. Other Securities 1,374,047.45\n4. Loans and Discounts 3,521,675.21\n5. Loans Secured by Real Estate 5,114,453.29\n6. Banking Houses, Vaults and Safes,\nFurniture and Fixtures and Other\nReal Estate Owned $2,404,544.32\n7. Other Assets $58,928.67\nTotal Assets $26,882,499.20\nLeaving a Surplus Above All\nRequirements of $3,543,561.49\n\nMEMBER. FEDERAL RESERVE SYSTEM\nMEMBER, FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nr\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, MONDAY, JANUARY 3, 1938\nMARKET BEGINS'\nNEW YEAR IN\nDULL SESSION\nWall Street Awaits\nPresident\u2019s Stand\nBy LESLIE GOULD\nNEW YORK. Jan. 3 (1.N.5.).\nTire stock market ushered in the\nNew Year today in an inauspicious\nmanner. A sluggish undertone\nprevailed, as Wall Street awaited\ni President Roosevelt\u2019s message\n'marking the start of the Seventy\nfifth Congress.\nEasier tendencies predominated\nat the opening, but the list\nsteadied later in the first hour\nunder influence of a bulge in avia\ntion shares. Sever of the high\npriced isues, however, continued\nunder pressure.\nTRADING IS SLOW\nThe tape barely moved along\nthrough the forenoon, as volume\nran at a full-day rate of about a\nhalf-million shares. Speculative\ninterest was expected to continue\nat an ebb until the contents of\nthe President\u2019s message to Con\ngress was disclosed.\nHonor of being th efirst stock\nsold in 1938 fell to the inactive\nBethlehem Steel 5 per cent pre\nferred, whic hopened at 14%, off\nfrom its previous close. The\ntransaction was for 100 shares.\nDouglas Aircraft climbed more\nthan a point to 41 before meeting\nprofit-taking. Boeing gained a\npoint while United Aircraft moved\nup a large fraction.\nPIVOTAL ISSUES\nTypical of fluctuations in pivotal\nissues were the movements in U.\nS. Steel and Chrysler. The former\nopened at 53%, off slipped\nto 53%, then climbed above its\nprevious close of 54. Chrysler,\nafter dropping a point to 46%,\nsnapped back to around 48 for a\nsmall fractional gain.\nWashington Stocks\nSALES\nAFTER CALL\nWashing on Gas Light, pre\nferred, <o@97.\nLIVERPOOL CLOSED\nLIVERPOOL, Jan. 3 (1.N.5.).\nThe Liverpool cotton exchange\nwas closed today.\nWashinqton Produce\nDAILY REPORT ON WASHINGTON\nEGG AND LIVE POLLTRY MARKET\n(Price, Paid Shlpperse-Net F. O. H.\nWashington)\nBy the U. S. Bureau of Agricultural\nEconomics\nEggs\u2014 Market weak. Prices 1 to m\ncents lower. Government graded and\ndated eggs: Whites, U. S. Extras, large.\n28*\u00a3c; U. S extras, mediums, 26c: U. S\nstandards, large, 27c; U. S. standards,\nmediums, 24c. Nearby ungraded eggs:\nCurrent receipts, 24\u00ae25c; white, 26\u00ae\n27c.\nLive Poultry\u2014 Market steady at un\nchanged prices. Fowl: Colored, aeavy.\n18c; No. 2s. 13c; leghorns. 14c; roosters,\n12\u00ae 13c. Chickens: Virginia rocks. 22\n\u00ae23c; Delaware rocks and ctosses. 22c;\nmixed colors. 18c. Guineas, 2 lbs. and\nover, 50!&55c; under 2 lbs.. 40\u00ae50c each.\nCapons, 7 lbs. and over. 28 30c; slips\nand undersizes, 22\u00ae 25c.\nL. C. L. express receipts at Washington.\n